## How to Blend Open-Source Libraries with Your Existing LLM Architecture
Using frontier cloud models (like Gemini 1.5 Pro or GPT-4o) for every single page layout and crop can become expensive and slow at scale. You can use open-source libraries as a local pre-processor or a fallback agent. [2, 3, 4] 

[ Scanned PDF ] ──> [ Local Open-Source (Surya/Marker) ] ──┬──> [ Fast Pass: Math & Structuring ]
                                                           └──> [ If Ambiguous/Failed ] ──> [ Gemini / Claude API ]

## 1. Visual Bounding Boxes via Local Open-Source (Surya)
Instead of passing the entire high-resolution PDF page to Gemini/GPT and asking it to guess coordinates or crop images, use Surya locally on your backend server.

* Why: It executes instantly on your own hardware without API latency.
* Implementation: Let Surya detect layout blocks (bboxes) for text, tables, and diagrams. Crop the diagram elements using a lightweight Python library like OpenCV. [5] 
* The API Savings: Instead of uploading a massive PDF page to an LLM, you only send the isolated diagram image snippet alongside the question text snippet to verify correctness.

## 2. Local Markdown & LaTeX Generation (Marker)
JEE papers heavily rely on complex matrices, integration symbols, and coordinate geometry notation.

* Why: Cloud LLMs sometimes hallucinate fine-grain sub-scripts or sub-indices in complex JEE Advanced math.
* Implementation: Run Marker locally to generate an initial Markdown text string containing the math formulas in LaTeX.
* The Hybrid Prompt: Pass Marker's local Markdown output directly into Gemini or Claude as context, rather than the raw image alone. Ask the LLM: "Verify this locally-extracted LaTeX code against the source image segment. Fix any misread subscripts or missing symbols." This uses fewer tokens, speeds up API response times, and yields near-100% accuracy.

------------------------------
## Advanced Production Schema for JEE CBT Systems
Because JEE Advanced includes unique marking patterns (Multiple Correct, Numerical Value, Matrix Match), your backend database needs to store structural layout metadata alongside raw question strings and diagram URLs.
Here is an optimized, platform-agnostic JSON structure that your open-source processors and cloud LLMs can collectively populate:

